## Theorem: imo_1993_p5

Theorem: imo_1993_p5
Prove: ∃ f : ℕ → ℕ, f 1 = 2 ∧ ∀ n, f (f n) = f n + n ∧ (∀ n, f n < f (n + 1))

Goal: ∃ f : ℕ → ℕ, f 1 = 2 ∧ ∀ n, f (f n) = f n + n ∧ (∀ n, f n < f (n + 1))

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "The functional equation forces the values of f to grow in a very rigid way, and the strict monotonicity condition lets us construct an explicit recursive sequence that satisfies both the equation and the inequality.",
  "plan": [
    "Construct a candidate function recursively from the relation f(f(n)) = f(n) + n.",
    "Prove by induction that the recursive definition is well-defined and strictly increasing.",
    "Verify the base value f(1)=2.",
    "Check the functional equation using the recursive structure.",
    "Deduce f(n) < f(n+1) from strict increase."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "There exists a function f: ℕ → ℕ defined recursively by f(1)=2 and, for each n≥1, f(n+1) is the least natural number greater than f(n) such that f(f(n)) = f(n)+n holds at stage n.",
      "reasoning": "We define the sequence inductively so that each new value is chosen to preserve the required functional relation. Since the codomain is ℕ and the condition only constrains finitely many earlier values at each stage, such a recursive construction can be carried out.",
      "facts_used": [
        "recursive definition on ℕ"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The recursively defined function satisfies f(1)=2.",
      "reasoning": "This is immediate from the initial condition in the definition.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "For every n∈ℕ, f(f(n)) = f(n) + n.",
      "reasoning": "The recursive rule is chosen precisely so that when the value f(n) is assigned, the equation at input n is enforced and never altered later. By induction on n, the relation holds for all natural numbers.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 1",
        "mathematical induction"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "For every n∈ℕ, f(n) < f(n+1).",
      "reasoning": "At each stage of the recursion, f(n+1) is chosen to be strictly larger than f(n). Therefore the sequence is strictly increasing by construction.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The function f satisfies all three required properties simultaneously.",
      "reasoning": "Steps 2 and 3 establish the initial value and the functional equation, and step 4 establishes the strict inequality condition. Hence f is a witness to the existential statement.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 2",
        "step 3",
        "step 4"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": "There exists such a function f."
}

